RetroDriveAA Cloudflare Worker Setup

Purpose
- This worker is only for the phone controller WebSocket relay.
- It does not handle game uploads.
- The Android app connects as role=car.
- The phone controller page connects as role=phone.

Project Files
- wrangler.toml: Worker and Durable Object binding configuration.
- src/index.js: WebSocket entrypoint and Durable Object room logic.
- README.md: Short existing overview.
- readme.me: This detailed deployment and integration guide.

How The Controller Path Works
- The app opens a WebSocket to /ws?session=<id>&role=car.
- The hosted phone controller page opens a WebSocket to /ws?session=<id>&role=phone.
- The Worker routes both connections into the same Durable Object room using the session id.
- The Durable Object forwards frames between the car and phone sockets.
- If a newer socket connects for the same role, the older socket is replaced.

What The Worker Does Not Do
- No DOS game upload handling.
- No PHP relay endpoints.
- No file storage.
- No authentication beyond the session id.

Prerequisites
- Node.js LTS installed.
- A Cloudflare account.
- Wrangler available through npm.

Install And Login
1. Open a terminal in cloudflare-worker.
2. Run npm install.
3. Run npx wrangler login.

Wrangler Configuration
- Current worker name is retrodrive-ws-relay.
- Durable Object binding name is RELAY.
- Durable Object class name is RelayRoom.
- Current compatibility date is set in wrangler.toml.

If you rename the Durable Object class or binding, update both:
- wrangler.toml
- src/index.js

Deploy
1. In cloudflare-worker run npx wrangler deploy.
2. After deploy, note the Worker URL, for example:
   wss://retrodrive-ws-relay.<your-subdomain>.workers.dev/ws

Verify The Worker
1. Open the root URL in a browser.
2. It should return:
   retrodrive relay online
3. Open a WebSocket client on two terminals.

Example test with wscat
Terminal A
  npx wscat -c "wss://<your-worker>.workers.dev/ws?session=test&role=car"

Terminal B
  npx wscat -c "wss://<your-worker>.workers.dev/ws?session=test&role=phone"

If you send a message in one terminal, it should appear in the other.

Phone Controller Page
- The Worker only relays WebSockets.
- The HTML controller UI is hosted separately.
- The app currently points at a hosted controller page through CONTROLLER_WEB_BASE_URL.
- That page expects these query parameters:
  session=<generated-session-id>
  ws=<base-worker-websocket-url>

The page then builds:
- <ws>?session=<id>&role=phone

Android App Integration
Update these fields in app/build.gradle.kts after deployment if your URLs change:
- CONTROLLER_WS_BASE_URL
- CONTROLLER_WEB_BASE_URL

Current examples in the app:
- CONTROLLER_WS_BASE_URL = wss://retrodrive.antoniadis.workers.dev/ws
- CONTROLLER_WEB_BASE_URL = https://retrodrive.code-odyssey.com/controller.html

Expected Runtime Flow
1. The DOS session starts the controller server in the app.
2. The app generates a session id.
3. The app shows a QR code pointing to the hosted controller page.
4. The user opens the page on the phone.
5. The car connects to the Worker as role=car.
6. The phone connects to the Worker as role=phone.
7. Input frames are relayed through the Durable Object room.

Common Problems
- 426 Expected WebSocket:
  The client hit /ws without a WebSocket upgrade request.

- 400 Missing session or role:
  The request URL is missing query parameters.

- 400 Invalid role:
  Only phone and car are accepted.

- QR page loads but controller does not connect:
  Check that CONTROLLER_WEB_BASE_URL is reachable from the phone.
  Check that the page passes ws and session into the WebSocket URL.
  Check that the Worker URL ends with /ws.

- Connection loops or replacements:
  The same role is connecting multiple times for one session.
  The Worker intentionally replaces the older socket.

Security Notes
- Session ids are not authentication.
- Anyone with a valid session id can attempt to connect.
- For production hardening, add a signed token or short-lived auth layer.
- Consider origin validation and rate limiting at the Worker layer.

